# File: specs/bug-replace-askuserquestion-with-escalation-when-specs-missing/feature.gherkin
#
# Generated from: specs/bug-replace-askuserquestion-with-escalation-when-specs-missing/requirements.md
# Issue: #85
# Type: Defect regression

@regression
Feature: Escalation instead of AskUserQuestion when specs missing in unattended-mode
  The /write-code skill previously called AskUserQuestion when spec
  files were not found, regardless of whether unattended-mode was active. In headless
  sessions (SDLC runner), this caused the session to hang indefinitely.
  This was fixed by adding an unattended-mode conditional to the missing-specs error
  path: output an escalation message in unattended-mode, preserve AskUserQuestion
  in interactive mode.

  # --- Bug Is Fixed ---

  @regression
  Scenario: Escalation message output in unattended-mode when specs are missing
    Given a project with `.claude/unattended-mode` present
    And no spec files exist at `specs/` for the target issue
    When `/write-code #42` is invoked
    Then the skill outputs a message containing "No specs found"
    And the message references `/write-spec` as the prerequisite step
    And the message ends with "Done. Awaiting orchestrator."
    And `AskUserQuestion` is not called

  # --- Related Behavior Still Works ---

  @regression
  Scenario: Interactive prompt preserved when unattended-mode is absent
    Given a project without `.claude/unattended-mode`
    And no spec files exist at `specs/` for the target issue
    When `/write-code #42` is invoked
    Then the skill calls `AskUserQuestion` to prompt the user
    And the prompt suggests running `/write-spec #42` first
    And no "Done. Awaiting orchestrator." message is output

  # --- Edge Case: Escalation message contains diagnostic context ---

  @regression
  Scenario: Escalation message identifies missing spec details
    Given a project with `.claude/unattended-mode` present
    And no spec files exist at `specs/` for the target issue
    When `/write-code #42` is invoked
    Then the escalation message identifies what is missing (spec directory or specific files)
    And the message includes the issue number being implemented
